[start section id="20112"]

Mr. Higginbotham has had resection of a grade 3 adenocarcinoma of the splenic flexure with involvement of 2 (of 44) regional lymph nodes.  I discussed these findings with him and his son, particularly with regard to the question of adjuvant chemotherapy.  I am concerned about use of adjuvant chemotherapy such as FOLFOX in this elderly man.  He already has some moderately-severe neuropathy with a lot of difficulty walking, and I do not think he is a candidate for any regimen using drugs such as oxaliplatin.  We discussed the use of multiple cycles of capecitabine, but I think even this has the possibility/probability of some significant toxicity with a relatively low increment of improvement in outlook.  All-in-all, I think adjuvant chemotherapy for this man carries some significant risks, not only to his overall health but also to his quality of life with minimal improvement in his risk of recurrent disease.  I think the best approach is observation at intervals.  He does have a schedule to be seen by his physicians, but at this point, I do not think there is a good argument for adjuvant chemotherapy in this man.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

[end section id="20112"]

